Your team is building an AI-powered document processing pipeline using Temporal. A senior engineer proposes using an AI coding agent (configured with the Temporal Developer Skill) to generate workflow code that includes retry policies and activity timeouts. During code review, the AI-generated workflow contains the following pattern in Go:

```go
func DocumentWorkflow(ctx workflow.Context, docID string) error {
    ao := workflow.ActivityOptions{
        StartToCloseTimeout: time.Minute * 5,
        RetryPolicy: &temporal.RetryPolicy{
            MaximumAttempts: 3,
        },
    }
    ctx = workflow.WithActivityOptions(ctx, ao)

    // AI generated: use current time for idempotency key
    idempotencyKey := time.Now().Unix()
    return workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ProcessDocument, docID, idempotencyKey).Get(ctx, nil)
}
```

The AI agent was configured with the Temporal Developer Skill but was using the Temporal Docs MCP Server for real-time documentation lookup. A junior engineer argues this code is fine because 'the AI used up-to-date docs.' What is the critical production problem with this AI-generated workflow code, and why does neither the Temporal Developer Skill nor the MCP Server guarantee its absence?
